        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-6">
        *Costs based on 2024 Texas averages. Actual costs vary by installer, location, and system specifications.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8">Net Metering in Texas</h3>
      <p class="mb-4">
        While Texas doesn't have mandatory net metering, many retail electricity providers (REPs) offer competitive buyback programs. The deregulated market works in your favor - you can shop around for the best solar buyback rates, which typically range from 8-12¬¢/kWh.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- HVAC Section -->
    <section id="hvac" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">HVAC Systems in Texas</h2>
      
      <p class="mb-4">
        Texas's extreme summer heat makes HVAC one of the largest energy expenses for homeowners. The average Texas home spends $1,800-2,400 annually on cooling alone. Upgrading to a high-efficiency system can reduce these costs by 30-50%.
      </p>

