    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6">Texas Solar & HVAC FAQ</h2>
      
      <div class="space-y-6">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">How much do solar panels cost in Texas?</h3>
          <p>The average cost for a residential solar system in Texas ranges from $12,500-20,000 before incentives, or $8,750-14,000 after the 30% federal tax credit. Final costs depend on system size, equipment quality, and installer. Texas residents typically install 5-8 kW systems for 2,000-2,500 sq ft homes.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Does Texas have net metering?</h3>
          <p>Texas doesn't have mandatory net metering, but the deregulated market works in your favor. Many retail electricity providers offer competitive solar buyback programs at 8-12¬¢/kWh. You can shop around for the best rates, and some providers offer specialized solar plans with premium buyback rates.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What SEER rating should I get for Texas?</h3>
          <p>For Texas's hot climate, we recommend minimum 16 SEER, with 18 SEER being ideal for maximum efficiency and savings. While higher SEER units cost more upfront ($1,200-2,000 more), they pay for themselves within 3-5 years through reduced electricity bills. Texas summers run AC units 8-10 months per year, making efficiency crucial.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">How long does solar installation take in Texas?</h3>
          <p>From contract signing to system activation, expect 6-12 weeks. This includes permitting (2-4 weeks), installation (1-3 days), and utility interconnection approval (2-6 weeks). Austin Energy is typically fastest (4-6 weeks total), while some rural coops can take 8-12 weeks.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">Will solar panels survive Texas hailstorms?</h3>
          <p>Yes. Modern solar panels are tested to withstand 1-inch hail at 50 mph. Most Texas installations use tempered glass panels rated for severe weather. Additionally, homeowners insurance typically covers hail damage to solar systems. In hail-prone areas like DFW, consider panels with enhanced impact resistance.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2">What's the ROI on solar in Texas?</h3>
          <p>Texas solar installations typically achieve 6-7 year payback periods with 15-20% annual returns. A $15,000 system (after tax credit) saving $2,100/year pays for itself in 7.1 years. With 25-30 year panel warranties, you're looking at 18-23 years of "free" electricity and $38,000-48,000 in lifetime savings.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
